definition[0]: to take goods, letters, packages etc to a particular place or person
example[0]: The morning mail has just been delivered.
example[2]: I’m having some flowers delivered for her birthday.
example[3]: They set off to deliver supplies to an isolated village.
definition[1]: to do or provide the things you are expected to, because you are responsible for them or they are part of your job
example[4]: the costs of delivering adequate nursing care
example[5]: the failure of some services to deliver the goods (=do what they have promised)
example[6]: The company will deliver on its promises.
definition[2]: to help a woman give birth to her baby, or to give birth to a baby
example[7]: They rushed her to hospital where doctors delivered her baby.
definition[3]: to give something such as a blow, shock, or warning to someone or something
example[8]: He delivered a strong warning about the dangers facing the government.
definition[4]: to put someone into someone else’s control
example[9]: Sharett had betrayed him and delivered him to the enemy.
definition[5]: to get the votes or support of a particular group of people in an election
example[10]: He cannot deliver the Latino vote.
definition[6]: to help someone escape from something bad or evil
definition[7]: to take goods or mail to a place
example[12]: An average of 52 tankers a day deliver 462 million gallons of crude oil, gasoline and other petroleum products to the U.S.
example[13]: The new computers will be delivered next week.
definition[8]: to provide or achieve something that other people benefit from
example[14]: Since January 2005, the fund has delivered an annual return of 14.7%.
example[15]: Good government can deliver a high level of services while maintaining fiscal discipline.
example[16]: The question is whether the company can deliver on these commitments.
